This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of Natural Language Processing (cs.CL) because it proposes a new deep neural network architecture for sentence relation modeling that leverages pre-trained word embeddings and auxiliary character embeddings to learn sentence meanings. Additionally, the paper uses bidirectional LSTM and temporal CNN to construct matching features and learn high-level hidden matching feature representations. 

The paper could also belong to the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) because it uses deep neural networks to learn sentence representations and matching features. 

Furthermore, the paper could be categorized under Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) because it proposes a new approach to improve the quality of matching feature representation in sentence relation modeling. 

The sub-category of Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) is also a possibility because the paper uses neural networks to construct matching features and learn hidden representations. 

Finally, the sub-category of Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition (cs.CV) is a potential fit because the paper uses convolutional neural networks to learn high-level hidden matching feature representations.
